                                Report abuseTranscript of William H. CrawfordWilliam H. CrawfordPROCLAMATION Presidential Election 1824I, William H. Crawford, From Nelson County, Virginia. I achievement great knowledge while attending Moses Waddel's Carmel Academy and Richmond Academy. I later served as secretary of war and secretary of treasury.Whereas, I gained strong support among the senators and congress, even particularly the Old Republicans. Whereas, I was a powerful supporter of the movement in 1811 to recharter the Bank of the United States.Whereas, I have mixed feelings about emigration, but the new lands offered great wealth among speculators.Whereas, As part of the great cabinets, we want to improve the relationship with Great Britain.Whereas, Later in the running to be president I suffered a stroke.Even though I did suffer a stroke, I am still a great political leader. I have great views and beliefs. I do believe I can bring this nation to great success.General Political Atmosphere –1824• All candidates were democratic-republicans, marking the end of the republican-federalist political party.• 1824 election said to be the beginning of the 2 party system.Issues:o Monroe Doctrineo Western expansiono Suffrage for White MenPolitical Background• His political career started in 1799, when he was appointed to write digest of Georgia laws• In 1803 he won a seat in the Georgia legislature• In 1807 he went to Washington to fill the seat of the deceased senator Abraham Baldwin• He was elected to a full term as senator in 1811• When vice president George Clinton died in 1812, he was elected president pro tempore of the senate• In 1815, he was appointed secretary of war by James Madison• The next year, he became secretary of treasuryEconomic Policy•In 1791, Congress chartered the Bank of the United States for twenty years•In 1810, the bank had to be re-chartered     – March 4, 1811 was the expiration date     –Gallatin, Secretary of Treasury urged to recharter bank    --Many opponents and complications• Crawford Promoted the first bank of the U.S. in 1811   –      Supported the Bank System          –      Thought it was dangerous             to let the big states rule the            country   – Believed the power of tax          belonged to the states• Re-charted in 1816Personal Background• William H. Crawford was born in Amherst county, Virginia, on February 24, 1772. The sixth kid out of 11 born to Joel Crawford and Fanny Harris Crawford. When Crawford was 7 years old, the family moved to Edgefield, South Carolina, and 4 years later to Columbus county, Georgia. After his father’s death in 1788, Crawford split time teaching school and farming as he tried to support his family for 6 years.• Crawford then went and moved to Augusta, to attend Moses Waddle's Carmel Academy for 2 years. He then became principal at one of the largest schools in Augusta, studied law and was admitted to the Georgia Bar in 1798. Crawford became a lawyer a year later and opened a Law practice in Lexington, Georgia.• Interested in politics more than laws, he then went to complete a digest of the Georgia laws of 1755 to 1800.William H. CrawfordAmerican Bank SystemSlavery & Native AmericansStrongly in support of slavery; owned 45 slavesBelieved in sending all freed slaves back to AfricaLike Andrew Jackson, wanted to push the Native Americans off the land that was theirs because they were killing colonistsForeign PolicySupported President Madison's embargo against Great Britain & FranceServed as U.S. Minister to France for 2 yearsLater became Secretary of WarCrawford's CriticismCriticism on the American Bank SystemSecond BankMany state governments regarded the national bank as unresponsive to local needs, and many western settlers and urban worker’s remembered bitterly the bank’s conservative credits policies during the panic of 1819.Crawford was seen as “enemy to the principle of scattering banks profusely over the whole surface of the interior.”First BankRepublican opponents of the bank, particularly the South, believed that the bank was an “unconstitutional manifestation of federal power dangerous to democratic institutions.”Criticism on Foreign PolicyPeople did not want to go into war and therefore, not agreeing with the embargo act being removedFederalists believed that war would be almost as unpopular as the embargoNot many agreed that war was the only alternative to the embargoOther Candidates WeaknessesJacksonresented National BankMurderer?ClayHalf-educated, gambler, alcoholic, and womanizer"American System" argued unconstitutional and creates unwanted competition in the WestQuincy Adams"Dirty Deal" with Clay"Cold" personality and not socialFull transcriptPopular presentationsSee more popular or the latest prezisProductCompanyCareersSupportCommunityContactApps
